    <fr:title text="Noetherian condition is affine local">Noetherian condition is affine local</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Being <fr:link href="/schm-P1M1/" title="Noetherian and locally Noetherian schemes" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-P1M1/" display-uri="schm-P1M1" type="local">Noetherian</fr:link> is an <fr:link href="/schm-C6GR/" title="Affine local properties" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-C6GR/" display-uri="schm-C6GR" type="local">affine local</fr:link> property.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  Since Noetherian distributive lattices are closed under quotients, the first condition of affine local is trivial. Now suppose we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigvee _{i\in  I}a_i = 1]]></fr:tex> with each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/a_i]]></fr:tex> Noetherian. Any finite ascending sequence in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> induces inifinite ascending sequences in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_i]]></fr:tex>, which must be stationary by assumption. Since the family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{A_i\}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> is finite, they must have a common upper bound where all sequences being stationary. This implies the original sequence must be stationary, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is Noetherian.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
