   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>10</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  It suffices to observe that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/idem-comm-JOTR/" title="Noetherian distributive lattice" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-JOTR/" display-uri="idem-comm-JOTR" type="local">Noetherian distributive lattice</fr:link> iff <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex> is a Noetherian topological space. This holds by <fr:link href="/idem-comm-HLDT/" title="Frame of opens of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" /></fr:link> that closed subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex> are dually isomorphic to ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. Then it suffices to observe a finite union of Noetherian topological spaces is again Noetherian.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
